{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_bellatrix_ver03/data/sn89075140/00516993315/1937111801/0475.xml":{"full_text":"Church Calendar\nSt. Patrick's\n(t:30 A M. UtM\nPresbyterian Church\nElgar Shaffner, Superintendent.\nMrs. *Mna Davis, Ass't. Supt.\nThelma L. Rothgeb, Secretary\nJosephine Davis, A**s\u2019t Secc\u2019y.\nC. L Laskey, Treasurer.\nMrs. Ama Conrad, Pluilst\nArlene Gill, Chorister.\nRichard Box, Ass't. Chorister\nStinoay School 9:30 A. M.\nUnlc 1 Prayer Services every Wed\nnesday evening from 8 to 9 In the\nhome of Mr. and Mrs. S. H. King.\nYou ere cordially invited.\nMethodist Church\nRev. Hodge, Pastor.\nMrs. Zaidie Commers, Supt.\nHoward Evans, Ass't. Supt.\nKathleen Billings, Secretary.\nFlossie Hastings, Ass\u2019t Secretary.\nMrs. Lillie Gregg, Treasurer.\nMrs. Merle Parsons, Pianist.\nHoward Evans, Chorister.\nChurch service, 9:30.\nt Sunday School, 10:30.\nAlternate Sundays, Sunday School,\n9:30.\nft\nWest Hope\nSunday School 9:30 A. M.\nMorning Worship 10:30 A. M.\nChristian Endeavor 7:00 P. M.\nCustar Zion Lutheran\nWilliam Young, Pastor.\nMartin Stauffer, Superintendent.\nDivine service, 9:00 A. M.\nTheme: \u201cTo Him Be Glory and Do\nminion.\"\nSunday School, 10:00 A. M.\nLadies\u2019 Aid, Wednesday afternoon.\nVisitors are always welcome.\nFull Uospel Church\nMilton Center, Ohio\nMr. and Mrs. W. B. Steams, Pastors\nSunday Services:\n9:30 A. M. Sunday School. F. J.\nLas ha way. Superintendent.\n10:30 Morning Worship.\n7:30 P. M. Young People\u2019s meeting.\nChildren's meeting.\n8:00 P. M. Evangelistic Service.\nTuesday 8:00 P. M. Bible Study.\nFriday 8:00 P. M. Prayer Meeting.\nFull G impel Church\nOH School Bldg., Weston, Ohio\nMr. and Mrs. W. B. Steams, Pastors\nWednesday 7:30 P. M. Bible Study\nand Prr.yer meeting.\nG. R. School Ne.ws\nContinued from First Page\nsis now is being placed on how to lay\nout a pattern, fitting, and the use of\nthe sewing machine.\nBesides regular class work, each\ngirl in the senior class is carrying on\nan outside project. For this project\neach girl chooses some activity in\nwhich she is interested and carries it\non outside of class. Class time is not\nused for this work but help and refer\nence work Is given by the teacher.\nAt the end of a definite period of\ntime, each project will be exhibited\nand criticised by the class. Some of\nthe prolects being undertaken are:\nreflnlshing of furniture, remodeling\nof clothing, meal planning and pre\nparation. and the making of Christ\nmas gifts.\nThe years course for ths senior\nclass will include a study of manners\nand etiquette, textiles, colors, sewing\nexperiences, some food work, health\nstudies, home furnishings, home nurs\ning, and some child study.\nThe girls in the class made cur\nuuncu muru i^nuruu\n(Custar Parish)\nHarold T. Bartlett, Pastor\nMorning Worship 9:30.\nSunday School 10:30\nMalinta Church\nSunday School 9:30 A. M.\nEvening Worship 7:30 P. M\nThe CLA-ZEL\nBOWLING GREEN\nWed.-Thurs.-Frl\u2014Nov. 17-18*19\nEDDIE CANTOR\nIn\n\u201cAU BABA GOES TO TOWN\u2019*\nSaturday Open 2:18 Nov. 20\n\"THE LADY ESCAPES\nAlso\n\"FORLORN RIVER\u201d\nSun.-Mon.\u2014 Open 2:18 Sunday\nNov. 21-22\nBING CROSBY\nMARTHA RATE\nIn\n\u201cDOUBLE WEDDING\u201d\nTuesday Open 4:00 pan. Nov. 28\nBANK NIGHT\n\u2018THE WOMEN MEN MARRY\u201d\nAlso\n\u201cSOPHIE LANG GOES WEST*\nWed.-Thur.-Frt. Nov. 24-28-26\nOpen 2:18 Thanksgiving\nIRENE DUNNE\nRANDOLPH SCOTT\ni _ In\n\u201cHIGH. WIDE AND\nHANDSOME\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK FOR THE COUNTRY\nTHEY RISE AND FALL TOGETHER\nFarm Cash Income V Income of Industrial workers.\nme}SLn i i i i i i i i ii\u2014:\u2014i\nctnm\nEconomists Say ohlo Farmers\nHave Better Position Than\nProducers elsewhere\nIn adapting government business\noutlook reports to Ohio farm condi\ntions, members of the Ohio State Uni\nversity rural economics department\nsay, \"The average Ohio farmer is in\na better economic position than the\naverage United States farmer for the\nnext 12 months. The Ohio farmer has\nrelatively large supply of livestock\nand also has a fairly large feed supply\n\"The 1934 and 1936 droughts for\nced considerable liquidation of live\nstock in the drouth areas; and from\nJanuary 1, 1934 to January 1, 1937,\nthe number of cattle and calves in the\nUnited States declined 11 per cent but\nthere was a decrease of only 2 per\ncent in the numbers of cattle and cal\nves in Ohio. Farmers in the whole na\ntion reduced the numbers of milk\ncows by 7 per cent but the numbers\ndecreased only 2 per cent in Ohio;\nand the number of hogs on farms in\nOhio declined only 11.6 per cent while\nthe decline was 27 per cent for the\ncountry as a whole.\n\u201cThe presence of the fairly large\nnumbers of livestock in Ohio and the\nprospects for continuing good prices\nmake the Ohio farmers\u2019 positions re\nlatively secure for the coming year.\nCrop production was good In the state\nir. 1937 and farmers have a large sup\nply of feeds to market through their\nlivestock.\u201d\nNational economic authorities say,\n\u2022The demand for farm products prob\nably will not be as favorable in 1938\na3 it was in 1937. This outlook is bas\ned upon an analysis of the general\nsituation, which Indicates that the up\nswing of the business cycle has been\ntemporarily halted in the fall of 1937.\n\u201cIncreased supplies of farm pro\nducts in the United States and de\ncreased supplies available in foreign\ncountries should result in a materially\nlarger volume of agricultural ex\nports from this country in 1938. Both\nbuying prices and buying power per\nunit of farm products are expected\nto be lower In 1938. The total nation\nal income for 1938 is expected to be\nbelow the high level of $69,000,000,\n000 which prevailed in 1937.\n\"Some slackening in the rate of\nautomobile production in 1938 as com\npared with 1937 may ocour. A large\npotential demand for steel products\nfrom railroads is indicated by the ca\npacity and condition of existing equip\nment and roadbed in relatior to pros\npective traffic needs but this demand\nwill become effective only as the vol\nume of traffic and net earnings make\npracticable the financing of replace\nments and improvements.\n\"Building activity experiences cy\ncle swings which seems to be of\nlonger duration than the business cy\ncle. The bottom of the present con\nstruction cycle apparently was reach\ned in 1932-34, and an irregular ad\nvance is expected for several years.\nIn 1938, the total volume of construc\ntion is expected to be slightly greater\nthan in 1937.\n\"Many of the conditions which in\nthe past have been associated with\nthe ending of a major upswing in\nbusiness activity are absent now.\nBusiness debts are low, credit is\ncheap and plentiful, banking resour\nces are not strained, there is no build\ning boom, and there has been an ab\nsence of violent speculation of the\ntype which frequently preceedes the\nend of a business boom.\n\"There also are a number of un\nfavorable indications in the general\nsituation. The stimulus for rises in\nbusiness activity at various times\nsince 1933 has come, to a very con\nsiderable extent, from government\nspending, deficit financing, and mone\ntary measures. The bonus distribution\nin 1936 undoubtedly proved to be a\nmaterial stimulus to business in 1936\nWith tendency to curtail government\nspending and the expansion of credit\nby deficit through banks, such stimuli\nare likely to play a less prominent\npart in business advances during the\nnext few years.\n\"The level of wholesale prices in\nthe United States is expected to be\nlower in 1938 ti^an in 1937, with pros\npective lower prices for raw materials\nfarm products, and some kinds of\nmanufactured goods more than off\nsetting higher prices for some lines\nof finished and semi-finished products\nRetail prices probably have not yet\nreflected all the rice in wholesale pri\nces of manufacturing products and in\nmarketing costs.\n\"Indications point to some further\nincreases in retail prices of furniture\nfurnishings, shoes, and fuel. The ef\nfect on living costs of these increases\nprobably will be offset in part by low\ner prices of rayon and cotton clothing\nmeats, and some other foods. The\nrise in rents is expected to continue\nbut perhaps at a slower rate.\n\u201cThe general trend of prices for\nfarm products has been downward\nsince January, 1937; and in Septem\nber the index number of farm prices\nwas 118 compared with 124 in Sep\ntember, 1936. Farm prices are expect\ned to average lower in 1938 than in\n1937. Prices paid by farmers in Sep\ntember were about 130 per cent ol\npre-war and three points higher than\na year earlier. Some further advance\nin prices paid by farmers may occui\nin 1938 so that the buying power ol\nfarm income is not expected to be as\nhigh as in 1937.\ntains for the home economics room,\nthey have gotten flowers for the\nwindows and put up pictures to make\nthe room more cheerful and home-like\nThe department has three new sew\nng machines, an electric iron, Iron\ning board and a dressing room for\nthe girls to use in fitting garments.\nA home economics club has been or\nganized for all the girls. They hold\na regular meeting every two weeks\nat the school and are planning out\nside activities such as suppers, par\nties and other affairs. One aim of the\nclub is to puchase new things for the\ndepartment It recently purchased a\npinking attachment for the sewing\nmachine.\nThe Junior class has started re\nhearsals for their play, \u201cSmall Town\nRomeo\" which will he presented on\nFriday evening, December 3rd. This\nplay written by Al. W. Clark is a\nthree act comedy and is being direc\nted by Miss Marcella Steiner. Mem\nbers of the cast are: Richard Box,\nOrval Weaver, Jack Katon, Wilbur\nHeyman, Helen Jeffers, Margaret\nWarner, Josephine Davis, Charlotte\nJeffers, Nelva Culbertson, and Harold\nGerdes. Watch for the full cast and\nparticulars in a later issue and plan\nnow to attend.\nThe local basketball team opened\nthe season by playing Haskins here\non Friday evening. The teams were\ndefeated by the superior teams of\ntheir opponent school the scores be\ning: first boys team, 38-17, second\nboys team, 19-17, and girls team 12\n10. The local school will Journey to\nWhitehouse to play this Friday even\ning. The next home game will be with\nMilton Center on the evening of Nov.\n34th.\nFourth Grade\u2014Fart Fox and Ches\nter Brown are back in school. We are\nvisiting Nandla in Baffin Island, in\nGeography.\nFifth\u2014Charles Carlan, Gloria Alt,\nand Ervin Hummel are back in\nschool following: a two week\u2019s absence\nwith measles. We are starting a pro\nducts map of the United States ln'oui\nGeography class.\nMrs. Ruth Huffman led the Union\nPrayer services held at the home of\nMr. and Mrs. S. H. King on Wednes\nday evening. Mrs. Fordyce Rager will\nlead the services next week.\nMr. and Mrs. Ortez Gallagher were\nsix o\u2019clock dinner guests of Mr. and\nMrs. John Smarts of Toledo, Tuesday\nevening.\nMonday evening, Mr. and Mrs. Or\ntez Gallagher entertained Mr. and\nMrs. E. O. Powell and Mr. and Mrs.\nDon Miller of Bowling Green follow\ning the P T. A. meeting.\nProduction of all fruits in the Uni\nted States for the next five years is\nexpected to exceed production for the\nperiod 1932-36 but demand for fruit\nalso should be higher in the years a\nhead than for the past five years.\nEnglish poultry dressing establish\nments have found that certain me\nthods of electrocuting poultry makes\nthe task of removing the feathers\nmuch easier. Bruising of flesh occurs\nless often with this system than with\nthe more usual methods.\nTexas farmers and ranchmen have\napproved an extension project of\ngame management by setting aside\n1,597,600 acres for game preserve de\nmonstrations. Deer, antelope, wild\nturkeys, prairie chicken, quail and\nother forms of wild life will be inves\ntigated as possible crops for this kind\nof land.\nFarmers cannot obtain any govern\nment to permit inoculation of hogr\nto prevent cholera nor as reimbur\nsement for hogs which have been vic\ntims of that disease.\nOhio State University will give 14\n\"'hart courses In agricultural subjects\nduring the winter months. They are\nlesigned to present in two or three\ndays, information of vital interest to\nceople who can leave their work on\nly for a short time. Complete infor\nmation about them can be obtained\nfrom the office of Dean John F. Cun\nnigham.\nOne foot of hopper space for every\nfive hens in the laying house- will\ntend to decrease fighting and to in\ncrease egg production.\nNEED NAUTICAL TERM\nTO MAKE FARM PLANS\nDean John F. Cunningham Says\nSailors Watch Midship Spoke\nTo Assure Straight Course\nMen who gather their harvest from\nthe sea tell whether the rudder is set\nto keep the ship on a straight course\nby watching the midship spoke on the\nwheel and Ohio farmers could derive\nconsiderable advantage if they also\nhad some sure way to tell whether\nihey are on the true course of pro\ncress, according to Dean John F.\nCunningham, Ohio State University.\nDean Cunningham believes the ag\nricultural ship can be sailed straight\nif enough study is made of farm prob\nlems, and he says that the promise\nof Secretary Henry A. Wallace to\ntravel a middle course with the nation\nall agricultural programs contains a\ngreat deal of encouragement to those\nwho are interested in rural prosperity.\nThe head of the University agri\nReddin and Reddin\nAttorneys and Abstractors\nPhone 4601 124 S. Mam Strer\nBOWLING GREEN, OHIO\ncultural collge says that one Im\nmediate problem confronting Ohio\nfarmers is to realize the tremendous\ndamage being done to their farms by\nsoil erosion and to adapt available\nmeans of slowing down this loss. He\nalso thinks that both industry and\nagriculture should have a better un\nderstanding of the relationship be\ntween them and the dependence of\neac\u00a3 upon the prosperity of the other.\nDean Cunningham says that far\nmers should participate in all plans\nmade to chart national courses for\nagriculture because their daily con\ntact with farm work enables them to\nforesee whether some proposals are\npractical or not. He warns against\nexpecting any agricultural panacea to\nimmediately quiet all troubled waters\nbut says that time should be .taken\nto lay out a true course to safe har\nbors.\nCOURT HOUSE HEWS\nContinued from First Page.\nasking payment on a promissory note\namounting to $3314.78 held on lot 392,\nEagle Farm Addition/ Rossford.\nAlbert Charles Milliron, Bowling\nGreen, has filed a divorce action in\nCommon Pleas court against Ruth\nMilliron, Toledo, charging gross ne\nglect of duty. The plaintiff charges\nthat the defendant has failed, neglect\ned and refused to live with him since\nAugust, 1937. They were married Au\ngust 26, 1936, at Auburn, Indiana and\nhave no children.\nCOMMON PLEAS ENTRIES\nSale confirmed in suit of J. Lee\nEwing against Commrecial Savings\nBank and Trust Company, et al.\nCase dismissed in suit of Sada H.\nSage against Vada Bermerkamp.\nDivorce granted plaintiff in suits of\nAbraham Toung against Minnie\nYoung; and Jerome DePre against\nMinnie DePre.\nTitle quieted in suit of Mennell\nMilling Co., against Alfred Thurstin,\net al.\nDivorce granted defendant in suit\nof Alfred Henry Haas against Laura\nHaas\nNEW CASES\nPearl B. Soash has brought suit\nagainst Ross Soash, asking for a di\nvorce on the grounds of gross neglect\nof duty and extreme cruelty. The pe- j\ntition says the couple was married\nDecember 24, 1906 and have two\nchildren. She asks for the divorce j!\nand enforcement of a post-nuptial j\nagreement.\nATTENTION FARMERS!\nWE PAY YOU CASH\n$1.00 for Horses $1.00 for Cattle\nSmall Stock Removed FREE\nCall Weston Fertilizer Co,\nPhono 231 Weaton day or night at our oxpenae\nAlways Prompt Reliable Service.\nSee our SUITS\nand OVERCOATS\nYou've always wanted a suit or coat as fine as these\nnow's your time to indulge that taste for the better things in\nlife.\nMEN\u2019S SUITS\nDouble breasted, fancy checks, plain brown and oxford shades. Priced\nfrom\n$16.50 TO $28.50\nSingle Breasted Suits\nIn all the wanted shades of brown, greys and blues. Fancy backs and\nyoung men\u2019s prep models, and man\u2019s coat styles.\n$16.50 TO $29.50\nBOYS\u2019SUITS\nFine selection of single and double breasted models. Size 16 to 19. Two\npair of trousers.\n$12.50 TO $22.50\nBoys\u2019 Topcoats and Overcoats. Sizes 12 to 17, single and double breasted\nmodels, full belt.\n$12.95 TO $14.95\nLandsdown Velvet Finish\nTopcoats\nWith full or half belt, made by Cur lee Clothiers. Colors of brown and\ngrey plaids; also dark oxford\u2014\n$24.75\nStandard Line of Topcoats\nv\nConsist of greys, grey and tan checks and dark oxfords.\n$10.50 TO $19.50\nBlue Melton and Oxford Overcoats for men, heavy and warm.\n$18.50\nQiey and brown plaid heavy overcoat. Wlnterhaven grade, fine styling","height":"26544","width":"18112"}}
